THE THREE HOUNDS (the mirror he does not have words for)
Hircine names each hunter's true beast, and he has named Saijah's:
the hound (The Hound and the Wolf, Section II). Varon ALREADY MADE
THAT TRADE. He lay awake while the chirurgeons carved him into a
hound for the Shadowscales -- the clipped ears, the shaved jaw, the
daily burn. Now a god is offering her the leash, shaped as a gift,
free to refuse. Three hounds stand in this story: Ylva (claimed
long ago, passed over), Varon (carved by mortal hands, never
asked), Saijah (courted, and free). Every outcome of her crossroads
detonates in him:
  - She ACCEPTS: she becomes what he became -- but blessed, chosen,
    ASKED. His surgery was the discount version of the gift she was
    offered for free. The Void never even bid.
  - She REFUSES and stays the hero: his standing nightmare -- proof
    his mutilation was unnecessary -- now with divine confirmation
    that she was worth courting.
  - She takes the THIRD PATH: the version of him that didn't break
    walks on with no god and no master -- the one thing the Colony
    taught him is impossible.
GM: he has no framework for any of this. Play it through the tells
(the hand, the blinking, the Jel) and never through speeches.

